<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="495" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d495">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 839.00/520.]</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister to the
                                    Dominican Republic</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Santo Domingo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-08">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 8, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The Dominican Government informs me that Horacio Vásquez<note n="1" xml:id="d495fn1">See <ref target="frus1911#pg_172">For. Rel. 1911,
                                    p. 172</ref>.</note> and the two Rodriguez left Porto Rico today
                            for Cuba, bound for Haiti, and that Vásquez will receive from the United
                            States via Cape Haitien 500,000 rounds and 1000 rifles.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Russell.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>